Classification of Petroleum: Classes "A-C" of petroleum are considered 
flammable and have a flash point of 80° F or below. Examples of these classes
range from very light napthas (Class A) to most crude oils (Class C). Class D 
cargoes such as kerosene and heavy crudes are considered combustible and have 
a flash point above 80° F but below 150° F. Class E cargoes are the heavier 
fuel oils and lubricating oils and have a flash point above 150° F.


